My morning started in a thick fog, both literally and figuratively. As a manager in my late 40s, I was driving to the station, picking him up‚Äîmy supervisor, a Silent Generation leader who still prefers a car ride over a Zoom call. He doesn't take anything for granted; he thanked me for the ride as if it were a huge favor, which is a trait I‚Äôve noticed in his generation‚Äîthey truly value every small effort.

When we arrived at the office, the atmosphere shifted. My younger colleagues, mostly Gen Zers, were already debating the merits of being a civil servant versus a freelancer. One intern argued that a government job is too rigid, while another mentioned that she places a high value on stability. Generally speaking, Millennials in our office tend to focus on work-life balance, but these younger ones seem more worried about the economy.

During a meeting, I noticed a disconnect regarding family values. My Boomer manager talked about staying late as a sign of loyalty, but my younger colleagues stared at their watches, eager to get off work at 6:00 PM sharp. To them, leaving on time is a right, not a lack of commitment. I tried to bridge the gap by suggesting that efficiency is more important than hours sat at a desk.

It was actually refreshing to hear a Gen Alpha intern‚Äîa high school shadow‚Äîsay that he just wants to do work that "matters." This disconnect often stems from how different eras shaped our view of a "career." By the time I finally got to get off work, the thick fog had cleared, leaving me with a better understanding of the five different worlds I navigate every day.
